# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: adjective
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was most recently revised for its ninth edition of 1940.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] Abridged versions and a supplement exist.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was initially the basis for the 2021 *Cambridge Greek Lexicon*, although subsequently that became a complete rewrite from scratch.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] The lexicon was begun in the 19th century, and is now in its ninth (revised) edition, published in 1940.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was based on the earlier *Handwörterbuch der griechischen Sprache* by the German lexicographer Franz Passow (first published in 1819, fourth edition 1831), which in turn was based on Johann Gottlob Schneider's *Kritisches griechisch-deutsches Handwörterbuch*.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] The *Lexicon* has served as the basis for all later lexicographical work on the ancient Greek language, such as the ongoing Greek–Spanish dictionary project *Diccionario Griego–Español* (DGE).
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] It is now conventionally referred to as *Liddell & Scott*, *Liddell–Scott–Jones*, or *LSJ*, and its three sizes are sometimes referred to as "The Little Liddell", "The Middle Liddell" and "The Big Liddell" or "The Great Scott".
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] The LSJ main edition has 116,502 entries.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] According to Stuart Jones's preface to the ninth (1925) edition, the creation of the *Lexicon* was originally proposed by David Alphonso Talboys, an Oxford publisher.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was published by the Clarendon Press at Oxford rather than by Talboys, who died before the first edition (1843) was complete.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] The first editor of the LSJ, Henry George Liddell, was Dean of Christ Church, Oxford, and the father of Alice Liddell, the eponymous Alice of the writings of Lewis Carroll.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] The eighth edition (1897) was the last edition published during Liddell's lifetime.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] The LSJ is sometimes compared and contrasted with *A Latin Dictionary* by Lewis and Short, which was also published by Oxford University Press (OUP).
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] It is also sometimes compared with the Bauer lexicon, which is a similar work focused on the Greek of the New Testament.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] The LSJ's definitions reflect the Victorian morality of its time, using euphemism.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] For example, χέζω (*chezo*, 'to shit'), is translated as "ease oneself, do one's need"; βινέω (*bineo*, 'to fuck') as "inire, coire, of illicit intercourse"; and λαικάζω (*laikazo*, 'to suck cocks') as "to wench".
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] Two condensed editions of LSJ were published by Oxford University Press and remain in print.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] In 1843, the same year as the full lexicon's publication, *A Lexicon: Abridged from Liddell and Scott's Greek–English Lexicon*, sometimes called "the Little Liddell" was published.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] For example, a reprint, re-typeset in 2007, of the 1909 edition is available from Simon Wallenberg Press.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] In 1889, an intermediate edition of the lexicon, *An Intermediate Greek–English Lexicon*, was prepared on the basis of the seventh edition (1883) of LSJ.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] After the publication of the ninth edition in 1940, and shortly after the deaths of both Stuart Jones and McKenzie, the OUP maintained a list of *addenda et corrigenda* ("additions and corrections"), which was bound with subsequent printings.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] However, in 1968, these were replaced by a Supplement to the LSJ.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] Neither the *addenda* nor the Supplement has ever been merged into the main text, which still stands as originally composed by Liddell, Scott, Jones, and McKenzie.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Supplement was initially edited by M.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] Glare, editor of the *Oxford Latin Dictionary* (not to be confused with Lewis and Short's *A Latin Dictionary*).
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] Since 1988, it has been edited by Glare and Anne A.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] As the title page of the *Lexicon* makes clear (and the prefaces to the main text and to the Supplement attest), this editorial work has been performed "with the cooperation of many scholars".
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Supplement primarily takes the form of a list of additions and corrections to the main text, sorted by entry.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] The supplemental entries are marked with signs to show the nature of the changes they call for.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] Thus, a user of the *Lexicon* can consult the Supplement after consulting the main text to see whether scholarship after Jones and McKenzie has provided any new information about a particular word.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] As of 2005, the most recent revision of the Supplement, published in 1996, contains 320 pages of corrections to the main text, as well as other materials.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] The small "x" indicates that this word did not appear in the main text at all; "S.*fr*." refers to the collected fragmentary works of Sophocles.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] One interesting new source of lexicographic material in the revised Supplement is the Mycenean inscriptions.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] The ninth edition of LSJ has been freely available in electronic form since 2007, having been digitized by the Perseus Project.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] Diogenes, a free software package, incorporates the Perseus data and allows easy offline consultation of LSJ on Mac OS X, Windows, and Linux platforms.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] Marcion is another open source application that includes the Perseus LSJ.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] For mobile devices, both the Kindle E-Ink and the iPhone/iPod Touch feature data ported from Perseus.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Android market also currently offers the intermediate LSJ as an offline downloadable app for free or for a small price.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] A CD-ROM version published and sold by Logos Bible Software also incorporates the Supplement's additions to the ninth edition of LSJ.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] A new online version of LSJ was released in 2011 by the Thesaurus Linguae Graecae (TLG).
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] The TLG version corrects "a large number of typographical errors", and includes links to the extensive TLG textual corpus.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] A Kindle version, the "Complete Liddell & Scott's Lexicon with Inflections", is also available: it allows searches of most Classical Greek word-forms and supports a growing number of Ancient/Classical Greek texts for the device.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Lexicon has been translated into Modern Greek by Xenophon Moschos, ed.: Michael Konstantinidis and was published by Anestis Konstantinidis in 1904 with the title *H.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] Scott – Α.* Κωνσταντινίδου (Μέγα Λεξικόν τῆς Ἑλληνικῆς Γλώσσης).
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] Also, a supplement compiled by a group of Greek philologists.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] An Italian translation of the *Intermediate Liddell-Scott*, entitled *Dizionario illustrato Greco-Italiano* was published in 1975 by Le Monnier, edited by Q.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] LSJ was the basis of the project of John Chadwick and James Diggle at Cambridge to publish the *Cambridge Greek Lexicon* of 2021.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] Although it was initially conceived as a mere update of LSJ, the editors eventually decided to start afresh since they considered LSJ "too antiquated in concept, design and content".
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] The CGL has a smaller scope than the LSJ (and also the *Brill Dictionary of Ancient Greek*), and is unlikely to replace it; however, it is still more comprehensive than the Middle Liddell, which it intends to replace.
[src:adjective/a-greek-english-lexicon] The *Cambridge Greek Lexicon* uses contemporary language for its definitions and, unlike the LSJ, no longer elides the meaning of words considered offensive in Victorian times.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] The work is usually referred to as *Lewis and Short* after the names of its editors, Charlton T.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] It was derived from the 1850 English translation by Ethan Allen Andrews of an earlier Latin–German dictionary, *Wörterbuch der Lateinischen Sprache*, by the German philologist Wilhelm Freund, in turn based on I.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] Scheller’s Latin–German dictionary of 1783.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] The Andrews translation was partially revised by Freund himself, then by Henry Drisler, and was finally edited by Short and Lewis.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] The division of labour between the two editors was remarkably unequal.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] In 1890 Lewis published a heavily abridged version of the dictionary, entitled *An Elementary Latin Dictionary*, for the use of students.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] Sometimes called the *Elementary Lewis*, it is still in print today.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] The adoption of the book by Oxford University Press was the result of the failure of its own project to create a new Latin–English dictionary in 1875.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] Henry Nettleship and John Mayor had been commissioned to produce a new Latin dictionary based on a fresh reading of the sources, but after Mayor withdrew from the project, Nettleship was unable to complete it on his own; he eventually published his research as notes on Lewis and Short.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] While the Press had earlier published John Riddle's 1835 translation of Scheller's Latin–German dictionary, this was a much more expensive book.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] The Press thus adopted *Harpers' Latin Dictionary* as a stopgap measure, paying Harper and Brothers 10 per cent royalties.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] Harper and Brothers sold its rights to the American Book Company in 1899, shortly before its bankruptcy.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] From the time of its publication, many scholars have criticized the dictionary for its errors and inconsistencies.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] Because of various circumstances, however, no replacement was attempted until 1933, with the *Oxford Latin Dictionary*, which was completed in 1983.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] However, the *Oxford Latin Dictionary* stops at 200CE.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] The dictionary's full text (year 1879) is available online at numerous websites.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] Among classicists "never a very good dictionary", Lewis and Short has been largely superseded by the *Oxford Latin Dictionary*, called the *OLD* for short.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] Lewis and Short incorporated material from existing Latin dictionaries; the *OLD*, by contrast, started from scratch, following procedures similar to those of the well-regarded *Oxford English Dictionary*.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] Thanks to the increased availability of modern editions, the *OLD* editors had access to a larger variety of classical works.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] It was decided in the *OLD'*s planning that the *OLD* would not encompass Latin written later than AD 200, with a few exceptions.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] Although classicists still consult Lewis and Short, they tend to prefer the *OLD*.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] Lewis and Short retains value for its refined sense of the nuances of English diction as it interfaces with Latin diction (in contrast with *OLD*'s preference for plainer diction) and also for the sensitivity of its quotations from classical texts, reflecting this.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] Lewis and Short's primary focus is on classical Latin, not medieval Latin.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] Nevertheless, Lewis and Short is consulted by medievalists, renaissance specialists, and early modernists, as it includes some late and medieval Latin, if somewhat inconsistently, and classical Latin usages are very relevant in medieval Latin.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] The *Dictionary of Medieval Latin from British Sources* supplements Lewis and Short for medieval Latin vocabulary.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] Another dictionary focused on medieval Latin is J.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] Niermeyer's **Mediae Latinitatis Lexicon Minus**, first published in 1976, with an enhanced second edition in year 2002, about 1500 pages.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] On occasion people confuse Lewis and Short (or L&S) with Liddell and Scott, its Greek counterpart, entitled *A Greek–English Lexicon*.
[src:adjective/a-latin-dictionary] The 1925 and later editions of Liddell and Scott are commonly referred to by the abbreviation *LSJ* after the names of its editors Liddell, Scott and the editor of the 1925 revision, Henry Stuart Jones.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] An **abbreviation** (from Latin **brevis** 'short') is a shortened form of a word or phrase, by any method including shortening, contraction, initialism (which includes acronym), or crasis.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] An abbreviation may be a shortened form of a word, usually ended with a trailing full stop (period).
[src:adjective/abbreviations] For example, the term *etc.* is the usual abbreviation for the Latin phrase *et cetera*.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] A *contraction* is an abbreviation formed by leaving out letters or sounds, typically replaced by an apostrophe in English.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Examples include *I'm* for *I am* and *li'l* for *little*.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] An *initialism* or *acronym* is an abbreviation consisting of the initial letter of a sequence of words without other punctuation.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] For example, FBI (/ˌɛf.biːˈaɪ/), USA (/ˌjuː.ɛsˈeɪ/), IBM (/ˌaɪ.biːˈɛm/), BBC (/ˌbiː.biːˈsiː/).
[src:adjective/abbreviations] When initialism is used as the preferred term, acronym refers more specifically to when the abbreviation is pronounced as a word rather than as separate letters; examples include SWAT and NASA.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Initialisms, contractions and crasis share some semantic and phonetic functions, and are connected by the term *abbreviation* in loose parlance.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] In early times, abbreviations may have been common due to the effort involved in writing (many inscriptions were carved in stone) or to provide secrecy via obfuscation.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Reduction of a word to a single letter was common in both Greek and Roman writing.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] In Roman inscriptions, "Words were commonly abbreviated by using the initial letter or letters of words, and most inscriptions have at least one abbreviation".
[src:adjective/abbreviations] However, "some could have more than one meaning, depending on their context.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Abbreviations were frequently used in early English.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Manuscripts of copies of the Old English poem *Beowulf* used many abbreviations, for example the Tironian et (⁊) or & for *and*, and y for *since*, so that "not much space is wasted".
[src:adjective/abbreviations] The standardisation of English in the 15th through 17th centuries included a growth in the use of such abbreviations.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] At first, abbreviations were sometimes represented with various suspension signs, not only periods.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] For example, sequences like ⟨er⟩ were replaced with ⟨ɔ⟩, as in mastɔ for *master* and exacɔbate for *exacerbate*.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] While this may seem trivial, it was symptomatic of an attempt by people manually reproducing academic texts to reduce the copy time.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] — Warden of Merton College, University of Oxford in *Registrum Annalium Collegii Mertonensis*, 1503.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] In the Early Modern English period, between the 15th and 17th centuries, the thorn Þ was used for *th*, as in Þe ('the').
[src:adjective/abbreviations] In modern times, ⟨Þ⟩ was often used (in the form ⟨y⟩) for promotional reasons, as in Ye Olde Tea Shoppe.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] During the growth of philological linguistic theory in academic Britain, abbreviating became very fashionable.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Likewise, a century earlier in Boston, a fad of abbreviation started that swept the United States, with the globally popular term OK generally credited as a remnant of its influence.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Over the years, however, the lack of convention in some style guides has made it difficult to determine which two-word abbreviations should be abbreviated with periods and which should not.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Widespread use of electronic communication through mobile phones and the Internet during the 1990s led to a marked rise in colloquial abbreviation.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] This was due largely to increasing popularity of textual communication services such as instant and text messaging.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] The original SMS supported message lengths of 160 characters at most (using the GSM 03.38 character set), for instance.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] This brevity gave rise to an informal abbreviation scheme sometimes called Textese, with which 10% or more of the words in a typical SMS message are abbreviated.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] More recently Twitter, a popular social networking service, began driving abbreviation use with 140 character message limits.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] In HTML, abbreviations can be annotated using a dedicated tag: `<abbr title="Editor">Ed.</abbr>` In this example, the meaning of "Ed." as "Editor" is revealed by hovering the cursor over it.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] In modern English, there are multiple conventions for abbreviation, and there is controversy as to which should be used.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] One generally accepted rule is to be consistent in a body of work.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] To this end, publishers may express their preferences in a style guide.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Some controversies that arise are described below.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] If the original word was capitalized then the first letter of its abbreviation should retain the capital, for example Lev. for *Leviticus*.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] When a word is abbreviated to more than a single letter and was originally spelled with lower case letters then there is no need for capitalization.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] However, when abbreviating a phrase where only the first letter of each word is taken, then all letters should be capitalized, as in YTD for *year-to-date*, PCB for *printed circuit board* and FYI for *for your information*.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] However, see the following section regarding abbreviations that have become common vocabulary: these are no longer written with capital letters.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] A period (full stop) is sometimes used to signify abbreviation, but opinion is divided as to when and if this convention is best practice.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] According to Hart's Rules, a word shortened by dropping letters from the end terminates with a full stop (period), whereas a word shorted by dropping letters from the middle does not.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Fowler's Modern English Usage says a full stop (period) is used for both of these shortened forms, but recommends against this practice.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] It advises it only for end-shortened words and lower-case initialisms, not for middle-shortened words and upper-case initialisms.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Some British style guides, such as for The Guardian and The Economist, disallow periods for all abbreviations.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] In American English, the period is usually included regardless of whether or not it is a contraction, e.g.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] *Dr.* or *Mrs.* In some cases, periods are optional, as in either *US* or *U.S.* for *United States*, *EU* or *E.U.* for *European Union*, and *UN* or *U.N.* for *United Nations*.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] There are some house styles, however—American ones included—that remove the periods from almost all abbreviations.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Acronyms that were originally capitalized (with or without periods) but have since entered the vocabulary as generic words are no longer written with capital letters nor with any periods.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Examples are sonar, radar, lidar, laser, snafu, and scuba.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] In the past, some initialisms were styled with a period after each letter and a space between each pair.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] There are multiple ways to pluralize an abbreviation.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Sometimes this accomplished by adding an apostrophe and an *s* ('s), as in "two PC's have broken screens".
[src:adjective/abbreviations] But, some find this confusing since the notation can indicate possessive case.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] And, this style is deprecated by many style guides.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] For instance, Kate Turabian, writing about style in academic writings, allows for an apostrophe to form plural acronyms "only when an abbreviation contains internal periods or both capital and lowercase letters".
[src:adjective/abbreviations] For example, "DVDs" and "URLs" and "Ph.D.'s", while the Modern Language Association explicitly says, "do not use an apostrophe to form the plural of an abbreviation".
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Also, the American Psychological Association specifically says, "without an apostrophe".
[src:adjective/abbreviations] However, the 1999 style guide for *The New York Times* states that the addition of an apostrophe is necessary when pluralizing all abbreviations, preferring "PC's, TV's and VCR's".
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Forming a plural of an initialization without an apostrophe can also be used for a number, or a letter.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] For units of measure, the same form is used for both singular and plural.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] When an abbreviation contains more than one period, *Hart's Rules* recommends putting the *s* after the final one.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] According to *Hart's Rules*, an apostrophe may be used in rare cases where clarity calls for it, for example when letters or symbols are referred to as objects.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] In Latin, and continuing to the derivative forms in European languages as well as English, single-letter abbreviations had the plural being a doubling of the letter for note-taking.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Most of these deal with writing and publishing.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] A few longer abbreviations use this as well.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Publications based in the U.S. tend to follow the style guides of *The Chicago Manual of Style* and the Associated Press.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] The U.S. government follows a style guide published by the U.S.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] The National Institute of Standards and Technology sets the style for abbreviations of units.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Writers often use shorthand to denote units of measure.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Such shorthand can be an abbreviation, such as "in" for "inch" or can be a symbol such as "km" for "kilometre".
[src:adjective/abbreviations] In the International System of Units (SI) manual the word "symbol" is used consistently to define the shorthand used to represent the various SI units of measure.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] A syllabic abbreviation is usually formed from the initial syllables of several words, such as *Interpol* = *International* + *police*.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Syllabic abbreviations are usually written using lower case, sometimes starting with a capital letter, and are always pronounced as words rather than letter by letter.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Syllabic abbreviations should be distinguished from portmanteaus, which combine two words without necessarily taking whole syllables from each.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Syllabic abbreviations are not widely used in English.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Some UK government agencies such as Ofcom (Office of Communications) and the former Oftel (Office of Telecommunications) use this style.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] New York City has various neighborhoods named by syllabic abbreviation, such as Tribeca (Triangle below Canal Street) and SoHo (South of Houston Street).
[src:adjective/abbreviations] This usage has spread into other American cities, giving SoMa, San Francisco (South of Market), and LoDo, Denver (Lower Downtown), amongst others.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Sections of California are also often colloquially syllabically abbreviated, as in NorCal (Northern California), CenCal (Central California), and SoCal (Southern California).
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Additionally, in the context of Los Angeles, the syllabic abbreviation SoHo (Southern Hollywood) refers to the southern portion of the Hollywood neighborhood.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Partially syllabic abbreviations are preferred by the US Navy, as they increase readability amidst the large number of initialisms that would otherwise have to fit into the same acronyms.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Hence *DESRON 6* is used (in the full capital form) to mean "Destroyer Squadron 6", while *COMNAVAIRLANT* would be "Commander, Naval Air Force (in the) Atlantic".
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Syllabic abbreviations are a prominent feature of Newspeak, the fictional language of George Orwell's dystopian novel *Nineteen Eighty-Four*.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] The political contractions of Newspeak—*Ingsoc* (English Socialism), *Minitrue* (Ministry of Truth), *Miniplenty* (Ministry of Plenty)—are described by Orwell as similar to real examples of German *(see below)* and Russian (*see below)* contractions in the 20th century.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] The contractions in Newspeak are supposed to have a political function by virtue of their abbreviated structure itself: nice sounding and easily pronounceable, their purpose is to mask all ideological content from the speaker.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] A more recent syllabic abbreviation has emerged with the disease COVID-19 (Corona Virus Disease 2019) caused by the Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (itself frequently abbreviated to SARS-CoV-2, partly an initialism).
[src:adjective/abbreviations] In Albanian, syllabic acronyms are sometimes used for composing a person's name, such as *Migjeni*—an abbreviation from his original name (*Millosh Gjergj Nikolla*) a famous Albanian poet and writer—or *ASDRENI* (*Aleksander Stavre Drenova*), another famous Albanian poet.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Other such names which are used commonly in recent decades are GETOAR, composed from *Gegeria* + *Tosks* (representing the two main dialects of the Albanian language, Gegë and Toskë), and *Arbanon*—which is an alternative way used to describe all Albanian lands.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Syllabic abbreviations were and are common in German; much like acronyms in English, they have a distinctly modern connotation, although contrary to popular belief, many date back to before 1933, if not the end of the Great War.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] *Kriminalpolizei*, literally *criminal police* but idiomatically the Criminal Investigation Department of any German police force, begat *KriPo* (variously capitalised), and likewise *Schutzpolizei* (*protection police* or *uniform department*) begat *SchuPo*.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Along the same lines, the Swiss Federal Railways' Transit Police—the *Transportpolizei*—are abbreviated as the *TraPo*.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] With the National Socialist German Workers' Party gaining power came a frenzy of government reorganisation, and with it a series of entirely new syllabic abbreviations.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Non regime-aligned partially syllabic abbreviations also existed like "Gröfaz" for the self-proclaimed "größter Feldherr aller Zeiten" (greatest military commander of all time), i.e.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] The new order of the German Democratic Republic in the east brought about a conscious denazification, but also a repudiation of earlier turns of phrase in favour of neologisms such as *Stasi* for *Staatssicherheit* ("state security", the secret police) and *VoPo* for *Volkspolizei*.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] The phrase *politisches Büro*, which may be rendered literally as "office of politics" or idiomatically as "political party steering committee", became *Politbüro*.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Syllabic abbreviations are not only used in politics, however.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Syllabic abbreviations are very common in Russian, Belarusian and Ukrainian.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] They are often used as names of organizations.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Historically, popularization of abbreviations was a way to simplify mass-education in 1920s (see Likbez).
[src:adjective/abbreviations] The word *kolkhoz* (*kollektívnoye khozyáystvo*, collective farm) is another example.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Leninist organisations such as the *Comintern* (*Communist International*) and *Komsomol* (*Kommunisticheskii Soyuz Molodyozhi*, or "Communist youth union") used Russian language syllabic abbreviations.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] In the modern Russian language, words like *Rosselkhozbank* (from Rossiysky selskokhozyaystvenny bank — Russian Agricultural Bank, RusAg) and *Minobrnauki* (from Ministerstvo obrazovaniya i nauki — Ministry of Education and Science) are still commonly used.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] In nearby Belarus, there are *Beltelecom* (Belarus Telecommunication) and Belsat (Belarus Satellite).
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Syllabic abbreviations are common in Spanish; examples abound in organization names such as Pemex for *Petróleos Mexicanos* ("Mexican Petroleums") or Fonafifo for *Fondo Nacional de Financimiento Forestal* (National Forestry Financing Fund).
[src:adjective/abbreviations] ("Banamex"), Teléfonos de México, S.A.B. de C.V.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] ("TELMEX"), Operadora de Cinemas, S.A. de C.V.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Malaysian abbreviation often uses letters from each word, while Indonesia usually uses syllables; although some cases do not follow the style.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] For example, general elections in Malaysian Malay often shortened into PRU (**p**ilihan **r**aya **u**mum) while Indonesian often shortened into pemilu (**pemil**ihan **u**mum).
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Another example is Ministry of Health in which Malaysian Malay uses KKM (**K**ementerian **K**esihatan **M**alaysia), compared to Indonesian Kemenkes (**Kemen**terian **Kes**ehatan).
[src:adjective/abbreviations] East Asian languages whose writing systems use Chinese characters form abbreviations similarly by using key Chinese characters from a term or phrase.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] For example, in Japanese the term for the United Nations, *kokusai rengō* (国際連合) is often abbreviated to *kokuren* (国連).
[src:adjective/abbreviations] (Such abbreviations are called ryakugo (略語) in Japanese; see also Japanese abbreviated and contracted words).
[src:adjective/abbreviations] The syllabic abbreviation of kanji words is frequently used for universities: for instance, *Tōdai* (東大) for *Tōkyō daigaku* (東京大学, University of Tokyo) and is used similarly in Chinese: *Běidà* (北大) for *Běijīng Dàxué* (北京大学, Peking University).
[src:adjective/abbreviations] Korean universities often follow the same conventions, such as *Hongdae* (홍대) as short for *Hongik Daehakgyo*, or Hongik University.
[src:adjective/abbreviations] The English phrase "Gung ho" originated as a Chinese abbreviation.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] In grammar, the **ablative case** (pronounced /ˈæblətɪv/ *AB-lə-tiv*; abbreviated **abl**) is a grammatical case for nouns, pronouns, and adjectives in the grammars of various languages.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] It is used to indicate motion away from something.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] In different languages it can additionally serve various other purposes, *e.g.*, to make comparisons (in Armenian).
[src:adjective/ablative-case] The word "ablative" derives from the Latin *ablatus*, the (suppletive) perfect, passive participle of *auferre* "to carry away".
[src:adjective/ablative-case] The ablative case is found in several language families, such as Indo-European (e.g.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] Sanskrit, Latin, Albanian, Armenian, Punjabi), Turkic (e.g.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] Turkish, Turkmen, Azerbaijani, Uzbek, Kazakh, Kyrgyz, Tatar), Tungusic (e.g.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] Hungarian), and the Dravidian languages.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] There is no ablative case in modern Germanic languages such as German and English.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] There was an ablative case in the early stages of Ancient Greek, but it quickly fell into disuse by the classical period.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] The ablative case in Latin (*cāsus ablātīvus*) appears in various grammatical constructions, including following various prepositions, in an ablative absolute clause, and adverbially.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] The Latin ablative case was derived from three Proto-Indo-European cases: ablative (from), instrumental (with), and locative (in/at).
[src:adjective/ablative-case] In Ancient Greek, there was an ablative case (ἀφαιρετικὴ πτῶσις *aphairetikē ptōsis*) which was used in the Homeric, pre-Mycenaean, and Mycenean periods.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] It fell into disuse during the classical period and thereafter with some of its functions taken by the genitive and others by the dative.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] The genitive case with the prepositions ἀπό *apó* 'away from' and ἐκ/ἐξ *ek/ex* 'out of' is an example.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] German does not have an ablative case but, exceptionally, Latin ablative case-forms were used from the seventeenth to the nineteenth century after some prepositions, for example after *von* in *von dem Nomine*: ablative of the Latin loanword *nomen*.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] Grammarians at that time, Justus Georg Schottel, Kaspar von Stieler, Johann Balthasar von Antesperg and Johann Christoph Gottsched, listed an ablative case (as the sixth case after nominative, genitive, dative, accusative and vocative) for German words.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] They considered the dative case after some prepositions to be an ablative, as in *von dem Mann[e]* 'from the man, of the man' and *mit dem Mann[e]* 'with the man', while they considered the dative case after other prepositions or without a preposition, as in *dem Mann[e]*, to be a dative.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] The ablative case is found in Albanian; it is the fifth case, *rasa rrjedhore*.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] In Sanskrit, the ablative case is the fifth case (*pañcamī*) and has a similar function to that in Latin.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] Sanskrit nouns in the ablative often refer to a subject "out of" which or "from" whom something (an action, an object) has arisen or occurred: *pátram **vṛkṣā́t** pátati* 'the leaf falls **from the tree**'.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] It is also used for nouns in several other senses, as for actions occurring "because of" or "without" a certain noun, indicating distance or direction.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] When it appears with a comparative adjective, (*śreṣṭhatamam* 'the best'), the ablative is used to refer to what the adjective is comparing: 'better than X'.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] The modern Armenian ablative has different markers for each main dialect, both originating from Classical Armenian.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] The Western Armenian affix -է *-ē* (definite -էն *-ēn*) derives from the classical singular; the Eastern Armenian affix -ից *-ic’* (both indefinite and definite) derives from the classical plural.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] For both dialects, those affixes are singular, with the corresponding plurals being -(ն)երէ(ն) *-(n)erē(n)* and -(ն)երից *-(n)eric’*.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] In Finnish, the ablative case is the sixth of the locative cases with the meaning "from, off, of": *pöytä – pöydältä* "table – off from the table".
[src:adjective/ablative-case] It is an outer locative case, used like the adessive and allative cases, to denote both being on top of something and "being around the place" (as opposed to the inner locative case, the elative, which means "from out of" or "from the inside of").
[src:adjective/ablative-case] With the locative, the receding object was near the other place or object, not inside it.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] The Finnish ablative is also used in time expressions to indicate times of something happening (*kymmeneltä* "at ten") as well as with verbs expressing feelings or emotions.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] The Finnish ablative has the ending *-lta* or *-ltä*, depending on vowel harmony.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] The ablative case in Estonian is the ninth case and has a similar function to that in Hungarian.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] The ablative case in Hungarian is used to describe movement away from, as well as a concept, object, act or event originating from an object, person, location or entity.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] When used to describe movement away from a location, the case may only refer to movement from *the general vicinity* of the location and not from inside of it.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] Thus, *a postától jövök* would mean one had been standing *next to* the post office before, not inside the building.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] When the case is used to refer to the origin of a possible act or event, the act/event may be implied while not explicitly stated, such as *Meg foglak védeni a rabló**tól***: I will defend you from the robber.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] The application of vowel harmony gives two different suffixes: *-tól* and *-től*.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] These are applied to back-vowel and front-vowel words, respectively.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] Hungarian has a narrower delative case, similar to ablative, but more specific: movement off/from a surface of something, with suffixes *-ról* and *-ről*.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] In some situations simple ablative can have a "because of" meaning; in these situations, ablative can be optionally followed by the postposition *dolayı* 'because of'.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] The ablative in Manchu is expressed through the suffix *-ci* and can also be used to express comparisons.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] It is usually not directly attached to its parent word.
[src:adjective/ablative-case] The ablative in Evenki is expressed with the suffix *-duk*.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] In linguistics, **apophony** is an alternation of vowel (quality) within a word that indicates grammatical information (often inflectional).
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] It is also known as **ablaut**, (**vowel**) **gradation**, (**vowel**) **mutation**, **alternation**, **internal modification**, **stem modification**, **stem alternation**, **replacive morphology**, **stem mutation**, or **internal inflection**.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] The difference in these vowels marks variously a difference in tense or aspect (e.g.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] *sing/sang/sung*), transitivity (*rise/raise*), part of speech (*sing/song*), or grammatical number (*goose/geese*).
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] That these sound alternations function grammatically can be seen as they are often equivalent to grammatical suffixes (an *external modification*).
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] The vowel alternation between *i* and *a* indicates a difference between present and past tense in the pair *sing/sang*.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Here the past tense is indicated by the vowel *a* just as the past tense is indicated on the verb *jump* with the past tense suffix *-ed*.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Likewise, the plural suffix *-s* on the word *books* has the same grammatical function as the presence of the vowel *ee* in the word *geese* (where *ee* alternates with *oo* in the pair *goose/geese*).
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Consonants, too, can alternate in ways that are used grammatically.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Most instances of apophony develop historically from changes due to phonological assimilation that are later grammaticalized (or morphologized) when the environment causing the assimilation is lost.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Such is the case with English *goose/geese* and *breath/breathe*.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Apophony may involve various types of alternations, including vowel quality, consonants, prosodic elements (such as tone and syllable length), or nasality (on vowels).
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] The sound alternations may be used inflectionally or derivationally.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] The particular function of a given alternation will depend on the language.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Indo-European ablaut (English *s**i**ng-s**a**ng*) and Germanic umlaut (*g**oo**se-g**ee**se*), mentioned above, are well attested examples.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] The vowel alternation may involve more than just a change in vowel quality.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] In Athabaskan languages, such as Navajo, verbs have series of stems where the vowel alternates (sometimes with an added suffix) indicating a different tense-aspect.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Navajo vowel ablaut, depending on the verb, may be a change in vowel, vowel length, nasality, and/or tone.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] For example, the verb stem *kaah/-ką́* 'to handle an open container' has a total of 16 combinations of the 5 modes and 4 aspects, resulting in 7 different verb stem forms (i.e.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Another verb stem | *-géésh/-gizh* 'to cut' has a different set of alternations and mode-aspect combinations, resulting in 3 different forms (i.e.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Various prosodic elements, such as tone, syllable length, and stress, may be found in alternations.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] English has alternating stress patterns that indicate whether related words are nouns (first syllable stressed) or verbs (second syllable stressed).
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Prosodic alternations are sometimes analyzed as not as a type of apophony but rather as prosodic affixes, which are known, variously, as *suprafixes*, *superfixes*, or *simulfixes*.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Consonant alternation is commonly known as consonant mutation or consonant gradation.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Bemba indicates causative verbs through alternation of the stem-final consonant.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Celtic languages are well known for their initial consonant mutations.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] In Indo-European linguistics, **ablaut** is the vowel alternation that produces such related words as s**i**ng, s**a**ng, s**u**ng, and s**o**ng.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] The difference in the vowels results from the alternation (in the Proto-Indo-European language) of the vowel *e* with the vowel *o* or with no vowel.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] To cite a few other examples of Indo-European ablaut, English has a certain class of verbs, called strong verbs, in which the vowel changes to indicate a different grammatical tense-aspect.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] As the examples above show, a change in the vowel of the verb stem creates a different verb form.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Some of the verbs also have a suffix in the past participle form.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] In Indo-European linguistics, **umlaut** is the vowel fronting that produces such related words as f**oo**t > f**ee**t or str**o**ng > str**e**ngth.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] The difference in the vowels results from the influence of an /i/, /iː/ or /j/ (which in most cases has since been lost) at the end of the word causing the stem vowel to be pulled forward.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Some weak verbs show umlaut in the present tense, with the past tense representing the original vowel: bought > buy (/ɔː/>/aɪ/).
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Hundreds of similar examples can be found in English, German, Dutch and other languages.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Germanic a-mutation is a process analogous to umlaut, but involving the influence of a low vowel such as /ɑ/ causing a high vowel in the stem to lower.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] In Indo-European historical linguistics the terms *ablaut* and *umlaut* refer to different phenomena and are not interchangeable.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] *Ablaut* is a process that dates back to Proto-Indo-European times, occurs in all Indo-European languages, and refers to (phonologically) unpredictable vowel alternations of a specific nature.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] From an Indo-European perspective, it typically appears as a variation between *o*, *e*, and no vowel, although various sound changes result in different vowel alternations appearing in different daughter languages.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] *Umlaut*, meanwhile, is a process that is particular to the Germanic languages and refers to a variation between back vowels and front vowels that was originally phonologically predictable, and was caused by the presence of an /i/ or /j/ in the syllable following the modified vowel.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] From a diachronic (historical) perspective, the distinction between ablaut and umlaut is very important, particularly in the Germanic languages, as it indicates where and how a specific vowel alternation originates.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] It is also important when taking a synchronic (descriptive) perspective on old Germanic languages such as Old English, as umlaut was still a very regular and productive process at the time.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] When taking a synchronic perspective on modern languages, however, both processes appear very similar.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] For example, the alternations seen in *sing/sang/sung* and *foot/feet* both appear to be morphologically conditioned (e.g. the alternation appears in the plural or past tense, but not the singular or present tense) and phonologically unpredictable.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Ambiguity can be avoided by using alternative terms (*apophony*, *gradation*, *alternation*, *internal modification* for *ablaut*; *vowel harmony* for *umlaut*) for the broader sense of the words.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Stem modifications (i.e. apophony) may co-occur with other morphological processes, such as affixation.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Here the singular/plural distinction is indicated through umlaut and additionally by a suffix *-er* in the plural form.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] The nonconcatenative morphology of the Afroasiatic languages is sometimes described in terms of apophony.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] The alternation patterns in many of these languages is quite extensive involving vowels and consonant gemination (i.e. doubled consonants).
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Other analyses of these languages consider the patterns not to be sound alternations, but rather discontinuous roots with discontinuous affixes, known as *transfixes* (sometimes considered *simulfixes* or *suprafixes*).
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Some theoretical perspectives call up the notion of morphological templates or morpheme "skeletons".
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] It would also be possible to analyze English in this way as well, where the alternation of *goose/geese* could be explained as a basic discontinuous root *g-se* that is filled out with an infix *-oo-* "(singular)" or *-ee-* "(plural)".
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Many would consider this type of analysis for English to be less desirable as this type of infixal morphology is not very prevalent throughout English and the morphemes *-oo-* and *-ee-* would be exceedingly rare.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Another analytical perspective on sound alternations treats the phenomena not as merely alternation but rather a "replacive" morpheme that replaces part of a word.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] In this analysis, the alternation between *goose/geese* may be thought of as *goose* being the basic form where *-ee-* is a replacive morpheme that is substituted for *oo*.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] This usage of the term *morpheme* (which is actually describing a replacement process, and not a true morpheme), however, is more in keeping with Item-and-Process models of morphology instead of Item-and-Arrangement models.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] And partially in eeny, meeny, miny, moe.
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] In many Turkic languages the vowel pattern is low to high, as in Turkish *ç**a**k-ç**u**k* (which follows the English pattern) and *f**a**n-f**i**n* (which contravenes it).
[src:adjective/ablaut-reduplication] Some languages do not appear to have a preferred order, for example Mongolian with both *p**a**y-p**u**y* and *p**u**y-p**a**y*.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] In philosophy, a fundamental distinction exists between **abstract** and **concrete** entities.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] While there is no universally accepted definition, common examples illustrate the difference: numbers, sets, and ideas are typically classified as abstract objects, whereas plants, dogs, and planets are considered concrete objects.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] *Causal influence* – Concrete objects can cause and be affected by other entities (e.g., a rock breaking a window), whereas abstract objects (e.g., the number 2) lack causal powers and do not cause anything to happen in the physical world.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] *Metaphysical relation* – In metaphysics, concrete objects are specific, individual things (particulars), while abstract objects represent general concepts or categories (universals).
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] *Ontological domain* – Concrete objects belong to the physical realm (or both the physical and mental realms), whereas abstract objects belong to neither.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] Another view is that it is the distinction between contingent existence versus necessary existence; however, philosophers differ on which type of existence here defines abstractness, as opposed to concreteness.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] Despite this diversity of views, there is broad agreement concerning most objects as to whether they are abstract or concrete, such that most interpretations agree, for example, that rocks are concrete objects while numbers are abstract objects.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] Abstract objects are most commonly used in philosophy, particularly metaphysics, and semantics.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] They are sometimes called ***abstracta*** in contrast to ***concreta***.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] The term *abstract object* is said to have been coined by Willard Van Orman Quine.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] Abstract object theory is a discipline that studies the nature and role of abstract objects.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] It holds that properties can be related to objects in two ways: through exemplification and through encoding.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] Concrete objects exemplify their properties while abstract objects merely encode them.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] This approach is also known as the dual copula strategy.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] The type–token distinction identifies physical objects that are tokens of a particular type of thing.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] The "type" of which it is a part is in itself an abstract object.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] Abstract objects have often garnered the interest of philosophers because they raise problems for popular theories.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] In ontology, abstract objects are considered problematic for physicalism and some forms of naturalism.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] Historically, the most important ontological dispute about abstract objects has been the problem of universals.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] In epistemology, abstract objects are considered problematic for empiricism.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] If abstracta lack causal powers and spatial location, how do we know about them?
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] It is hard to say how they can affect our sensory experiences, and yet we seem to agree on a wide range of claims about them.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] In philosophy of religion, the existence of abstract objects is sometimes considered a problem for divine aseity, which, for example, prompted the Christian philosopher William Lane Craig to argue against uncreated abstract objects.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] Other Christian philosophers, such as Peter van Inwagen, have conversely argued *for* their existence, seeing no conflict between them and theism.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] Some, such as Ernst Mally, Edward Zalta and arguably, Plato in his Theory of Forms, have held that abstract objects constitute the defining subject matter of metaphysics or philosophical inquiry more broadly.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] To the extent that philosophy is independent of empirical research, and to the extent that empirical questions do not inform questions about abstracta, philosophy would seem especially suited to answering these latter questions.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] In modern philosophy, the distinction between abstract and concrete was explored by Immanuel Kant and G.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] Gottlob Frege said that abstract objects, such as propositions, were members of a third realm, different from the external world or from internal consciousness.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] Another popular proposal for drawing the abstract–concrete distinction contends that an object is abstract if it lacks causal power.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] A causal power has the ability to affect something causally.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] Thus, the empty set is abstract because it cannot act on other objects.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] One problem with this view is that it is not clear exactly what it is to have causal power.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] For a more detailed exploration of the abstract–concrete distinction, see the relevant *Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy* article.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] In the 2010s, there was some philosophical interest in the development of a third category of objects known as the **quasi-abstract**.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] Quasi-abstract objects have drawn particular attention in the area of social ontology and documentality.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] Specifically, the ability to have temporal location, but not spatial location, and have causal agency (if only by acting through representatives).
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] These characteristics are exhibited by a number of social objects, including states of the international legal system.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] Jean Piaget uses the terms "concrete" and "formal" to describe two different types of learning.
[src:adjective/abstract-and-concrete] Concrete thinking involves facts and descriptions about everyday, tangible objects, while abstract (formal operational) thinking involves a mental process.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] In descriptions of the Japanese language, an **adjectival noun**, **nominal adjective**, **copular noun**, **adjectival verb** (形容動詞, *keiyō dōshi*), **quasi-adjective**, **pseudo-adjective**, or ***na*-adjective**, is a noun that can function as an adjective by taking the particle 〜な *-na*.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] (In comparison, regular nouns can function adjectivally by taking the particle 〜の *-no*, which is analyzed as the genitive case.) Adjectival nouns constitute one of several Japanese word classes that can be considered equivalent to adjectives.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] In their attributive function, Japanese adjectival nouns function similarly to English noun adjuncts, as in "*chicken* soup" or "*winter* coat" – in these cases, the nouns "chicken" and "winter" modify the nouns "soup" and "coat", respectively.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] Japanese adjectival nouns can also be used predicatively – in that use, they do not take the *-na* suffix, but normally combine with forms of the copular verb.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] The current term for the so-called "adjectival nouns" is *keiyō dōshi* (形容動詞).
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] 'form' or 'figure' or 'appearance' or 'description') refers to the semantic aspect of these words as qualifying the state or condition of a noun (名詞, *meishi*); and *dōshi* (動詞; lit.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] Historically, this term was used tentatively by some grammarians, such as Matsushita Daizaburō, for words that are now called *keiyōshi* (形容詞; lit.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] The "attributive adjective" sense was applied in a different way by yet other grammarians, such as Hamada Kenjirō and Ōwada Takeki, who used *keiyō dōshi* for "verb" forms that occur attributively, such as *hashiru* (走る; lit.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] The first use of *keiyō dōshi* for so-called "*na*-adjectives" is attributed to Haga Yaichi.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] The Japanese term is not necessarily at odds with the English term *adjectival noun*, since in traditional Japanese grammar, *keiyō dōshi* includes the copula, while the adjectival noun in the analysis described here does not include the copula.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] For example, in the traditional grammar, *kirei da* is a keiyō dōshi and *kirei* is its stem; in the analysis here, *kirei* is an adjectival noun and *kirei da* is its combination with the copula.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] Considering the copula is a kind of verb and *kirei* is a kind of noun syntactically, both terminologies make sense.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] Grammatically, these words are similar to nouns, or more technically, nominals, which function attributively (like adjectives).
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] Aside from these differences, Japanese adjectival nouns and regular nouns behave the same way in terms of grammar.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] They are variously referred to as "adjectival verbs" (literal translation), "adjectival nouns" (nouns that function adjectivally), "*na* adjectives" (function as adjectives, take *na*), and "*na* nominals" (nominals that take *na*).
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] For example, Eleanor Harz Jorden refers to them as "*na*-nominals" in her textbook *Japanese: The Spoken Language*.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] In fact, by some analyses, nouns and *na*-nominals are fundamentally grammatically the same, where 〜の vs. 〜な when used attributively is simply a conventional stylistic complementary distribution, with 〜の／〜な being allomorphs.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] This view is reinforced by the fact that some words, such as 特別 *tokubetsu* "special", can take either a 〜の or a 〜な, depending on the phrase.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] Ultimately, 〜な is an abbreviation of 〜にある, used to use a noun attributively (compare modern 〜である, which is a more recent form), while 〜の is the genitive case; see etymology, below.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] In traditional Japanese grammar, adjectival nouns are considered "inflectional", *katsuyō*, like verbs and *i*-adjectives, rather than non-inflectional *hikatsuyōgo* (非活用語) or *mukatsuyōgo* (無活用語), like nouns.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] This is a point of disagreement in current Japanese grammar, and authors such as Uehara (1998) argue that instead, adjectival nouns should be classed with nouns as non-inflectional.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] The claim that *na*-adjectives are inflectional rests on the claim that the syllable *da* 'is', usually regarded as a "copula verb", is really a suffix – an inflection.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] Thus, *hon* 'book', generates a one-word sentence, *honda* 'it is a book', not a two-word sentence, *hon da*.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] However, numerous constructions seem to be incompatible with the suffixal copula claim.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] In Japanese, questions are formed by adding the particle *ka* (or in colloquial speech, just by changing the intonation of the sentence).
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] On the basis of such constructions, Uehara (1998) finds that the copula is indeed an independent word, and that regarding the parameters on which *i*-adjectives share the syntactic pattern of verbs, the nominal adjectives pattern with pure nouns instead.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] In Late Old Japanese (below), a separate kind of *tari* adjectival nouns developed alongside the existing *nari* ones (*nari, tari* were the conclusive forms, while *naru, taru* were the attributive forms).
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] These are generally referred to as ト・タル形容動詞 (*to, taru keiyōdōshi*) or タルト型活用 (*taruto-kata katsuyō* – “taru, to form conjugation”), and can also function adverbially with 〜と *-to,* instead of the 〜に *-ni* which is mostly used with な nominals.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] See *taru* adjectives for further discussion in English, and 形容動詞#タルト型活用 for Japanese.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] A few *nari* adjectival nouns followed a similar path to *tari* adjectival nouns, becoming *naru* adjectives in Modern Japanese (analogous to *taru* adjectives), rather than *na* adjectives as most *nari* adjectival nouns did.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] Old Japanese has one type of adjectival noun with the following inflections.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] Late Old Japanese has two types of adjectival nouns: *nar-* and *tar-*.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] The newly developed *tar-* inflections are used in kanbun kundoku (reading a Chinese text in Japanese).
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] Early Middle Japanese has two types of adjectival nouns: *na-* and *tar-*.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] Late Middle Japanese has two types of adjectival nouns: *na* and *t-*.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] The early half of Early Modern Japanese as exhibited in the Kamigata region has a single type of adjectival noun with the following inflections.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] The later half of Early Modern Japanese as found in Edo has a single type of adjectival noun with the following inflections.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] These forms are identical to the modern forms.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] There is one type of adjectival noun in modern usage, with inflections as follows.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] Japanese adjectival nouns differ in etymological origin from adjectival verbs.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] Whereas adjectival verbs are almost entirely native in origin, the class of adjectival nouns comprises mostly foreign loanwords and a small subset of polymorphemic native words.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] All words listed in this section take the attributive *-na* and predicative *-da* copula.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] In addition to loanwords, within the class of adjectival nouns also exists a small subset of native Japanese words (wago).
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] These words are argued to be polymorphemic in nature, with the latter *-ka*, *-raka*, *-yaka* being a suffix that creates an adjectival noun.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] Nishiyama (1999) asserts that this helps to distinguish native adjectival nouns from native adjectival verbs.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] All forms of the copula (the vehicle for the inflection of adjectival nouns) can be considered to derive from two infinitive forms, *ni* and *to*.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] Because the copula lacked any other forms, secondary conjugations with the verb *ari* were used.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] The original *ni ari* and *to ari* contracted to form *nari* and *tari*.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] To derive the modern forms *na* and *da*, changes such as the following have been proposed.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] The infinitive form *ni* is still in widespread use (e.g.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] *hen ni naru*, "become strange"), but the form *to* has become a much rarer alternative for use with adjectives.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] The internal properties of Japanese adjectival nouns can be analysed either through a lexical features approach or through a Distributed Morphology approach.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] Miyagawa argues that Japanese adjectival nouns can be classified using Noam Chomsky's lexical feature system.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] Under this system, Japanese adjectival nouns are classed similarly to English pure adjectives [+V, +N].
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] However, because Japanese also has adjectival verbs with the lexical property [+V], it is observed that Japanese adjectival nouns and English pure adjectives are distinct.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] Within the tree structures, the word root combines with the functional category n0 to become a noun, then combine with the functional head a0 to form an adjective.
[src:adjective/adjectival-noun-japanese] Both nouns and adjectives contain the root-n0 combination, and it is the presence of a0 that results in the appearance of the attributive copula *-na*.
[src:adjective/adjective] An **adjective** (abbreviated **ADJ**) is a word that describes or defines a noun or noun phrase.
[src:adjective/adjective] Its semantic role is to change information given by the noun.
[src:adjective/adjective] The adjective is considered one of the main parts of speech of the English language, although historically they were classed together with nouns.
[src:adjective/adjective] Nowadays, certain words that usually had been classified as adjectives, including *the*, *this*, *my*, etc., typically are classed separately, as determiners.
[src:adjective/adjective] Depending on the language, an adjective can precede a corresponding noun on a prepositive basis or it can follow a corresponding noun on a postpositive basis.
[src:adjective/adjective] Structural, contextual, and style considerations can impinge on the pre-or post-position of an adjective in a given instance of its occurrence.
[src:adjective/adjective] Adjectives feature as a part of speech (word class) in most languages.
[src:adjective/adjective] In some languages, the words that serve the semantic function of adjectives are categorized together with some other class, such as nouns or verbs.
[src:adjective/adjective] In the phrase *a Ford car*, *Ford* is unquestionably a noun but its function is adjectival (noun adjunct, see below): to modify *car*.
[src:adjective/adjective] In some languages adjectives can function as nouns: for example, the Spanish phrase *un rojo* means 'a red [one]'.
[src:adjective/adjective] This is also possible in English, see above.
[src:adjective/adjective] As for "confusion" with verbs, rather than an adjective meaning "big", a language might have a verb that means "to be big" and could then use an attributive verb construction analogous to "big-being house" to express what in English is called a "big house".
[src:adjective/adjective] Such an analysis is possible for the grammar of Standard Chinese and Korean, for example.
[src:adjective/adjective] Different languages do not use adjectives in exactly the same situations.
[src:adjective/adjective] For example, where English uses *"*to be *hungry*" (*hungry* being an adjective), Dutch, French, and Spanish use "*honger hebben*", "*avoir faim*", and "*tener hambre*" respectively (literally "to have hunger", the words for "hunger" being nouns).
[src:adjective/adjective] Similarly, where Hebrew uses the adjective זקוק‎ (*zaqūq*, roughly "in need of" or "needing"), English uses the verb "to need".
[src:adjective/adjective] In languages that have adjectives as a word class, it is usually an open class; that is, it is relatively common for new adjectives to be formed via such processes as derivation.
[src:adjective/adjective] However, Bantu languages are well known for having only a small closed class of adjectives, and new adjectives are not easily derived.
[src:adjective/adjective] Similarly, native Japanese adjectives (*i*-adjectives) are considered a closed class (as are native verbs), although nouns (an open class) may be used in the genitive to convey some adjectival meanings, and there is also the separate open class of adjectival nouns (*na*-adjectives).
[src:adjective/adjective] Many languages (including English) distinguish between adjectives, which qualify nouns and pronouns, and adverbs, which mainly modify verbs, adjectives, or other adverbs.
[src:adjective/adjective] Not all languages make this exact distinction; many (including English) have words that can function as either.
[src:adjective/adjective] For example, in English, *fast* is an adjective in "a *fast* car" (where it qualifies the noun *car*) but an adverb in "he drove *fast*" (where it modifies the verb *drove*).
[src:adjective/adjective] A German word like *klug* ("clever(ly)") takes endings when used as an attributive adjective but not when used adverbially.
[src:adjective/adjective] Whether these are distinct parts of speech or distinct usages of the same part of speech is a question of analysis.
[src:adjective/adjective] While German linguistic terminology distinguishes *adverbiale* from *adjektivische Formen*, German refers to both as *Eigenschaftswörter* ("property words").
[src:adjective/adjective] Linguists today distinguish determiners from adjectives, considering them to be two separate parts of speech (or *lexical categories*).
[src:adjective/adjective] Determiners formerly were considered to be adjectives in some of their uses.
[src:adjective/adjective] Determiners function neither as nouns nor pronouns but instead characterize a nominal element within a particular context.
[src:adjective/adjective] They generally do this by indicating definiteness (*a* vs.
[src:adjective/adjective] An adjective acts as the head of an *adjective phrase* or *adjectival phrase* (AP).
[src:adjective/adjective] In the simplest case, an adjective phrase consists solely of the adjective; more complex adjective phrases may contain one or more adverbs modifying the adjective ("*very* strong"), or one or more complements (such as "worth *several dollars*", "full *of toys*", or "eager *to please*").
[src:adjective/adjective] In English, attributive adjective phrases that include complements typically follow the noun that they qualify ("an evildoer *devoid of redeeming qualities*").
[src:adjective/adjective] In many languages (including English) it is possible for nouns to modify other nouns.
[src:adjective/adjective] Unlike adjectives, nouns acting as modifiers (called *attributive nouns* or *noun adjuncts*) usually are not predicative; a beautiful park is beautiful, but a car park is not "car".
[src:adjective/adjective] The modifier often indicates origin ("*Virginia* reel"), purpose ("*work* clothes"), semantic patient ("*man* eater") or semantic subject ("*child* actor"); however, it may generally indicate almost any semantic relationship.
[src:adjective/adjective] It is also common for adjectives to be derived from nouns, as in *boyish*, *birdlike*, *behavioral (behavioural)*, *famous*, *manly*, *angelic*, and so on.
[src:adjective/adjective] Many languages have participle forms that can act as noun modifiers either alone or as the head of a phrase.
[src:adjective/adjective] Sometimes participles develop into functional usage as adjectives.
[src:adjective/adjective] Examples in English include *relieved* (the past participle of *relieve*), used as an adjective in passive voice constructs such as "I am so *relieved* to see you".
[src:adjective/adjective] Other examples include *spoken* (the past participle of *speak*) and *going* (the present participle of *go*), which function as attribute adjectives in such phrases as "the *spoken* word" and "the *going* rate".
[src:adjective/adjective] Other constructs that often modify nouns include prepositional phrases (as in "a rebel *without a cause*"), relative clauses (as in "the man *who wasn't there*"), and infinitive phrases (as in "a cake *to die for*").
[src:adjective/adjective] Some nouns can also take complements such as content clauses (as in "the idea *that I would do that*"), but these are not commonly considered modifiers.
[src:adjective/adjective] For more information about possible modifiers and dependents of nouns, see Components of noun phrases.
[src:adjective/adjective] In Australian Aboriginal languages, the distinction between adjectives and nouns is typically thought weak, and many of the languages only use nouns, or nouns with a limited set of adjective-deriving affixes, to modify other nouns.
[src:adjective/adjective] In languages that have a subtle adjective-noun distinction, one way to tell them apart is that a modifying adjective can come to stand in for an entire elided noun phrase, while a modifying noun cannot.
[src:adjective/adjective] For example, in Bardi, the adjective *moorrooloo* 'little' in the phrase *moorrooloo* *baawa* 'little child' can stand on its own to mean 'the little one', while the attributive noun *aamba* 'man' in the phrase *aamba baawa* 'male child' cannot stand for the whole phrase to mean 'the male one'.
[src:adjective/adjective] In other languages, like Warlpiri, nouns and adjectives are lumped together beneath the nominal umbrella because of their shared syntactic distribution as arguments of predicates.
[src:adjective/adjective] The only thing distinguishing them is that some nominals seem to semantically denote entities (typically nouns in English) and some nominals seem to denote attributes (typically adjectives in English).
[src:adjective/adjective] In many languages, attributive adjectives usually occur in a specific order.
[src:adjective/adjective] In general, the adjective order in English can be summarised as: opinion, size, age or shape, colour, origin, material, purpose.
[src:adjective/adjective] Other language authorities, like the *Cambridge Dictionary*, state that shape precedes rather than follows age.
[src:adjective/adjective] Determiners and postdeterminers—articles, numerals, and other limiters (e.g.
[src:adjective/adjective] *three* blind mice)—come before attributive adjectives in English.
[src:adjective/adjective] Although certain combinations of determiners can appear before a noun, they are far more circumscribed than adjectives in their use—typically, only a single determiner would appear before a noun or noun phrase (including any attributive adjectives).
[src:adjective/adjective] Size – adjectives denoting physical size (e.g.
[src:adjective/adjective] Shape or physical quality – adjectives describing more detailed physical attributes than overall size (e.g.
[src:adjective/adjective] Colour – adjectives denoting colour or pattern (e.g.
[src:adjective/adjective] Origin – denominal adjectives denoting source (e.g.
[src:adjective/adjective] This means that, in English, adjectives pertaining to size precede adjectives pertaining to age ("little old", not "old little"), which in turn generally precede adjectives pertaining to colour ("old white", not "white old").
[src:adjective/adjective] This order may be more rigid in some languages than others; in some, like Spanish, it may only be a default (*unmarked*) word order, with other orders being permissible.
[src:adjective/adjective] Other languages, such as Tagalog, follow their adjectival orders as rigidly as English.
[src:adjective/adjective] The normal adjectival order of English may be overridden in certain circumstances, especially when one adjective is being fronted or with ablaut reduplication.
[src:adjective/adjective] For example, the usual order of adjectives in English would result in the phrase "the bad big wolf" (opinion before size), but instead, the usual phrase is "the big bad wolf".
[src:adjective/adjective] Owing partially to borrowings from French, English has some adjectives that follow the noun as postmodifiers, called postpositive adjectives, as in *time immemorial* and *attorney general*.
[src:adjective/adjective] Adjectives may even change meaning depending on whether they precede or follow, as in *proper*: "They live in a *proper town*" (a real town, not a village) vs.
[src:adjective/adjective] "They live in the *town proper* (in the town itself, not in the suburbs).
[src:adjective/adjective] In many languages, some adjectives are *comparable* and the measure of comparison is called *degree*.
[src:adjective/adjective] For example, a person may be "polite", but another person may be "*more* polite", and a third person may be the "*most* polite" of the three.
[src:adjective/adjective] The word "more" here modifies the adjective "polite" to indicate a comparison is being made, and "most" modifies the adjective to indicate an absolute comparison (a *superlative*).
[src:adjective/adjective] Among languages that allow adjectives to be compared, different means are used to indicate comparison.
[src:adjective/adjective] Some languages do not distinguish between comparative and superlative forms.
[src:adjective/adjective] Other languages allow adjectives to be compared but do not have a special comparative form of the adjective.
[src:adjective/adjective] In such cases, as in some Australian Aboriginal languages, case-marking, such as the ablative case, may be used to indicate one entity has more of an adjectival quality than (i.e.
[src:adjective/adjective] Another way to convey comparison is by incorporating the words "more" and "most".
[src:adjective/adjective] There is no simple rule to decide which means is correct for any given adjective, however.
[src:adjective/adjective] The general tendency is for simpler adjectives and those from Anglo-Saxon to take the suffixes, while longer adjectives and those from French, Latin, or Greek do not—but sometimes the *sound* of the word is the deciding factor.
[src:adjective/adjective] Many adjectives do not naturally lend themselves to comparison.
[src:adjective/adjective] For example, some English speakers would argue that it does not make sense to say that one thing is "more ultimate" than another, or that something is "most ultimate", since the word "ultimate" is already absolute in its semantics.
[src:adjective/adjective] Such adjectives are called *non-comparable* or *absolute*.
[src:adjective/adjective] Nevertheless, native speakers will frequently play with the raised forms of adjectives of this sort.
[src:adjective/adjective] Although "pregnant" is logically non-comparable (either one is pregnant or not), one may hear a sentence like "She looks more and more pregnant each day".
[src:adjective/adjective] Comparative and superlative forms are also occasionally used for other purposes than comparison.
[src:adjective/adjective] In Italian, superlatives are frequently used to put strong emphasis on an adjective: *bellissimo* means "most beautiful", but is in fact more commonly heard in the sense "extremely beautiful".
[src:adjective/adjective] Attributive adjectives and other noun modifiers may be used either *restrictively* (helping to identify the noun's referent, hence "restricting" its reference) or *non-restrictively* (helping to describe a noun).
[src:adjective/adjective] Here "difficult" is restrictive – it tells which tasks he avoids, distinguishing these from the easy ones: "Only those tasks that are difficult".
[src:adjective/adjective] In English, restrictiveness is not marked on adjectives but is marked on relative clauses (the difference between "the man *who recognized me* was there" and "the man, *who recognized me*, was there" being one of restrictiveness).
[src:adjective/adjective] In some languages, adjectives alter their form to reflect the gender, case and number of the noun that they describe.
[src:adjective/adjective] Here, a distinction may be made between attributive and predicative usage.
[src:adjective/adjective] In English, adjectives never agree, whereas in French, they always agree.
[src:adjective/adjective] Semanticist Barbara Partee classifies adjectives semantically as intersective, subsective, or nonsubsective, with nonsubsective adjectives being plain nonsubsective or privative.
